	<a href="http://trevor.typepad.com/blog/2004/04/the_23rd_5th_me.html">Trevor F. Smith - Exterior: The 23rd, 5th meme</a><br /><ol><br /><li>Grab the nearest book.</li><br /><li>Open the book to page 23.</li><br /><li>Find the fifth sentence.</li><br /><li>Post the text of the sentence in your blog along with these instructions.</li><br /></ol><br /><blockquote><br />"While that sometimes works for experts who find the right audience (see the box below), it rarely works for students learning to do and report research."<br /></blockquote><br />The preceding sentence and begining of the paragraph is<br /><blockquote><br />"Some beginning researchers imagine their readers are like the Zeppelin Club--eager to hear any information new to them."<br /></blockquote><br />The "(box below)" is three pages beyond that paragraph, and emphasizes that specialized audiences care about esoteric things, but that doesn't work for broader audiences.  <br /><blockquote><br />Booth, Wayne C., Colomb, Gregory G., Williams, Joseph M.  <em>The Craft of Research</em>,  ed.2.  University of Chicago Press (Chicago: 1995, 2003).&nbsp; ISBN 0-226-06568-5 pbk.<br /></blockquote><br />I would rather have reached for Michael Crichton's autobiographical <em>Travels</em>, but it simply wasn't the nearest.  And I can't resist:<br /><blockquote><br />"You mean these shoes here?"<br /></blockquote><br />[later: When <a href="http://www.praxis101.com/blog/">anderbill</a> took on this assignment, and linked to me, I started tracing backward through the sources to see where this started.&nbsp; I dug back about 8 levels and I think the chain of sources is simply broken.]<br>
